<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with another High D Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>



<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Let the High D leader know you value his/her time.<br>
&#149;	Provide solutions, not problems.<br>
&#149;	Use straightforward communication.<br>
&#149;	Provide options and possibilities, not pre-ordained answers.<br>
&#149;	Allow the leader to make decisions.<br>
&#149;	Stress the what, not the why. Emphasize logic.<br>
&#149;	Remember that there can be only one king of the mountain, and the High D 
leader is it.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High I Leader… 
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>



<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Loosen up. High I leaders want to know what you think and how you feel about 
things.<br>
&#149;	Be more friendly, warm, and tactful than you usually are. Don't be abrupt or curt.<br>
&#149;	Don't impose your ideas. Be prepared to brainstorm.<br>
&#149;	Involve High I leaders in important, new, or highly visible projects.<br>
&#149;	Don't try to usurp the limelight or the initiative.<br>
&#149;	Be tolerant of the High I leader's casual use of time.<br>
&#149;	Show how your ideas will make the organization look good or provide attention 
and recognition.<br>
&#149;	Don't do all the talking. Provide opportunities for give and take.<br>
&#149;	Be willing to listen, and listen attentively.<br>
&#149;	Be willing to digress and chat more than you normally do.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

