<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High S Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>


<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Take an interest in the High S, both as a leader and as a person.<br>
&#149;	Be tolerant of the High S leader's predictable, steady pace.<br>
&#149;	Give plenty of advance warning when you want to make changes.<br>
&#149;	Express sincere appreciation for your leader's contributions.<br>
&#149;	Provide assurances; be warm, friendly, and sincere.<br>
&#149;	Be prepared to deal with more facts, details, and established procedures than 
usual.<br>
&#149;	Continue to take the initiative, but be less aggressive and more patient than 
usual.<br>
&#149;	Be prepared to work cooperatively and in a group to achieve common goals.<br>
&#149;	Tone down your natural bluster and abruptness, but not your enthusiasm or 
optimism; <br>
&#149;	High S leaders like a stable, calm atmosphere.<br>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>

<%=AppModParaFont%>
<%=AppModTitleFont%>
To work better with a High C Leader…
<%=EndAppModTitleFont%>
<%=EndAppModParaFont%>



<%=AppModParaFont%>
&#149;	Deal in logic, facts, and proof, not "gut feelings."<br>
&#149;	Don't be pushy or move to the bottom line too quickly.<br>
&#149;	Be tolerant of your leader's thoroughness. It may help you avoid serious trouble.<br>
&#149;	When you want to take a risk, provide probabilities and other data.<br>
&#149;	Don't be vague or casual, particularly when answering questions.<br>
&#149;	Provide written proposals for major decisions. Give him or her time to think.<br>
&#149;	Concentrate on reliability, security, and quality.<br>
&#149;	In advancing your ideas, appeal to logic, showing facts and benefits.<br>
&#149;	Don't be abrupt or speak too loudly.<br>
&#149;	When possible and practical, stay within established guidelines and procedures<br>
